<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-29T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-29T04:00:00-05:00" n="233" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1143</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Morgenthau</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-29T11:00:00+02:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">October 29, 1914, 11 a.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 12:15 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>British Ambassador has just received a telegram from Cairo that Bedouins
                            have crossed frontier on their way to Suez Canal. He writes me it may
                            mean war unless his demand to the Grand Vizier to immediately withdraw
                            Bedouins is complied with.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>